@article{Pfaehler2025,
  abstract = {<p> <italic>Objective.</italic> Conventionally, if two metabolic processes are of interest for image analysis, two separate, sequential positron emission tomography (PET) scans are performed. However, sequential PET scans cannot simultaneously display the metabolic targets. The concurrent study of two simultaneous PET scans could provide new insights into the causes of diseases. <italic>Approach.</italic> In this work, we propose a reconstruction algorithm for the simultaneous injection of a <inline-formula> <tex-math> <?CDATA $\beta^\{+\}$?> </tex-math> <math overflow="scroll"> <mrow> <msup> <mi>β</mi> <mrow> <mo>+</mo> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math> </inline-formula> -emitter emitting only annihilation photons and a <inline-formula> <tex-math> <?CDATA $\beta^\{+\}$?> </tex-math> <math overflow="scroll"> <mrow> <msup> <mi>β</mi> <mrow> <mo>+</mo> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math> </inline-formula> - <italic>γ</italic> -emitter emitting annihilation photons and an additional prompt <italic>γ</italic> -photon. As in previous works, the <italic>γ</italic> -photon is used to identify events originating from the <inline-formula> <tex-math> <?CDATA $\beta^\{+\}$?> </tex-math> <math overflow="scroll"> <mrow> <msup> <mi>β</mi> <mrow> <mo>+</mo> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math> </inline-formula> - <italic>γ</italic> -emitter. However, due to e.g. attenuation and down-scatter, the <italic>γ</italic> -photon is often not detected and not all events can correctly be associated with the <inline-formula> <tex-math> <?CDATA $\beta^\{+\}$?> </tex-math> <math overflow="scroll"> <mrow> <msup> <mi>β</mi> <mrow> <mo>+</mo> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math> </inline-formula> - <italic>γ</italic> -emitter as they are detected as double coincidences. In contrast to previous works, we estimate this number of double coincidences with origin in the <inline-formula> <tex-math> <?CDATA $\beta^\{+\}$?> </tex-math> <math overflow="scroll"> <mrow> <msup> <mi>β</mi> <mrow> <mo>+</mo> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math> </inline-formula> - <italic>γ</italic> , emitter including the attenuation of the prompt <italic>γ</italic> , and incorporate this estimation in the forward-projection of the maximum likelihood expectation maximization algorithm. For evaluation, we simulate different scenarios with varying objects and attenuation maps. The nuclide <sup>18</sup> F serves as <inline-formula> <tex-math> <?CDATA $\beta^\{+\}$?> </tex-math> <math overflow="scroll"> <mrow> <msup> <mi>β</mi> <mrow> <mo>+</mo> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math> </inline-formula> -emitter, while <sup>44</sup> Sc functions as <inline-formula> <tex-math> <?CDATA $\beta^\{+\}$?> </tex-math> <math overflow="scroll"> <mrow> <msup> <mi>β</mi> <mrow> <mo>+</mo> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math> </inline-formula> - <italic>γ</italic> emitter. The performance of the algorithm is assessed by calculating the residual error of the <inline-formula> <tex-math> <?CDATA $\beta^\{+\}$?> </tex-math> <math overflow="scroll"> <mrow> <msup> <mi>β</mi> <mrow> <mo>+</mo> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math> </inline-formula> - <italic>γ</italic> -emitter in the reconstructed <inline-formula> <tex-math> <?CDATA $\beta^\{+\}$?> </tex-math> <math overflow="scroll"> <mrow> <msup> <mi>β</mi> <mrow> <mo>+</mo> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math> </inline-formula> -emitter image. Additionally, the intensity values in the simulated cylinders of the ground truth (GT) and the reconstructed images are compared. <italic>Main results.</italic> The remaining activity in the <inline-formula> <tex-math> <?CDATA $\beta^\{+\}$?> </tex-math> <math overflow="scroll"> <mrow> <msup> <mi>β</mi> <mrow> <mo>+</mo> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math> </inline-formula> -emitter image varied from 0.4% to 3.7%. The absolute percentage difference between GT and reconstructed intensity for the pure <inline-formula> <tex-math> <?CDATA $\beta^\{+\}$?> </tex-math> <math overflow="scroll"> <mrow> <msup> <mi>β</mi> <mrow> <mo>+</mo> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math> </inline-formula> emitter images was found to be between 3.0% and 7.4% for all cases. The absolute percentage difference between the GT and the reconstructed intensity for the <inline-formula> <tex-math> <?CDATA $\beta^\{+\}$?> </tex-math> <math overflow="scroll"> <mrow> <msup> <mi>β</mi> <mrow> <mo>+</mo> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math> </inline-formula> - <italic>γ</italic> emitter images ranged from 8.7% to 10.4% for all simulated cases. <italic>Significance.</italic> These results demonstrate that our approach can reconstruct two separate images with a good quantitation accuracy. </p>},
  author   = {Elisabeth Pfaehler and Debora Niekämper and Jürgen Scheins and N Jon Shah and Christoph W Lerche},
  doi      = {10.1088/1361-6560/ad9660},
  issn     = {0031-9155},
  issue    = {1},
  journal  = {Physics in Medicine \& Biology},
  keywords = {dual tracer PET,maximum-likelihood expectation maximization,positron emission tomography},
  month    = {1},
  pages    = {015009},
  title    = {ML-EM based dual tracer PET image reconstruction with inclusion of prompt gamma attenuation},
  volume   = {70},
  url      = {https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/1361-6560/ad9660},
  year     = {2025}
}
